snippet.textDisplay: I just searched about the female singer, whom I sadly didn't know till now, and the biggest shock that I got is that she is an assamese by birth and sings bhojpuri folk songs, but the amazing marwari that she has sung with such an ease is incredible. I am a marwari and trust me guys these kind of songs are so touchy here, that we are very sensitive about the singing and pronunciation quality, and I would say that the commendable talent of the female singer in particular has made me feel goosebumps. Marwari singing is not everybody's cup of tea, kudos to kalpana patowary...
snippet.textOriginal: I just searched about the female singer, whom I sadly didn't know till now, and the biggest shock that I got is that she is an assamese by birth and sings bhojpuri folk songs, but the amazing marwari that she has sung with such an ease is incredible. I am a marwari and trust me guys these kind of songs are so touchy here, that we are very sensitive about the singing and pronunciation quality, and I would say that the commendable talent of the female singer in particular has made me feel goosebumps. The meaning of the song is
Baisa ra beera means (Brother of my Sister in Law i.e my husband)
so in this song the lady saying that baisa re beera mujhe mayke la jao, kyunki maayke ki mujhe Olu aaye (yaad aaye).
And than she describes the lot of work her in laws are getting done from her like asking to fetch water etc.
